We start by defining \( A_n \) as the number of ways to tile a \( 1 \times n \) rectangle. The recurrence relation for \( A_n \) is given by: \[ A_n = A_{n-1} + A_{n-3} \] with base cases: \[ A_0 = 1, \quad A_1 = 1, \quad A_2 = 1 \] We compute the values of \( A_n \) step by step: \[ \begin{align*} A_3 & = A_2 + A_0 = 1 + 1 = 2, \\ A_4 & = A_3 + A_1 = 2 + 1 = 3, \\ A_5 & = A_4 + A_2 = 3 + 1 = 4, \\ A_6 & = A_5 + A_3 = 4 + 2 = 6, \\ A_7 & = A_6 + A_4 = 6 + 3 = 9, \\ A_8 & = A_7 + A_5 = 9 + 4 = 13, \\ A_9 & = A_8 + A_6 = 13 + 6 = 19, \\ A_{10} & = A_9 + A_7 = 19 + 9 = 28. \end{align*} \] We find that \( A_{10} = 28 \), which is the first value greater than or equal to 27. Therefore, the smallest \( n \) is 10. \[ \boxed{10} \]
